00:46.000 --> 00:53.000
All costs on the enterprise, depending on the change in the volume of production, can be divided into two groups.

00:53.000 --> 00:56.000
Constant and variable.

00:56.000 --> 00:59.000
Constant costs do not depend on the volume of production.

00:59.000 --> 01:04.000
No matter how much the volume of production increases, they remain unchanged.

01:04.000 --> 01:08.000
Constant costs are classified in different categories.

01:08.000 --> 01:17.000
For example, temporary wage, taxes, rent, administrative expenses.

01:18.000 --> 01:24.000
The second group of costs is variable costs.

01:24.000 --> 01:29.000
They change in proportion to the growth or reduction of the volume of production.

01:29.000 --> 01:34.000
If the enterprise increases production, its costs increase.

01:34.000 --> 01:39.000
If the volume of production decreases, the variable costs decrease.

01:39.000 --> 01:45.000
The group of variable costs includes the most various costs, but also the most important.

01:46.000 --> 01:48.000
The costs of raw materials.

01:48.000 --> 01:54.000
The more production is produced, the more costs are spent on raw materials.

01:54.000 --> 01:59.000
The cost of this group is the labor wage.

01:59.000 --> 02:05.000
The more production they produce, the more they pay for the production of this product.

02:05.000 --> 02:10.000
The same applies to fuel and energy.

02:11.000 --> 02:17.000
This is the simplest approach to determining the costs of constant and variable costs.

02:17.000 --> 02:24.000
The relationship between the costs of constant and variable costs can be imagined as follows.

02:24.000 --> 02:32.000
In this slide, you can see how the costs of constant and variable costs add up to form the total costs.

02:32.000 --> 02:43.000
You can see that the costs are equal to the sum of the costs of constant and variable costs multiplied by the volume of production.

02:43.000 --> 02:50.000
This is how the total costs of the enterprise are formed.

02:50.000 --> 02:54.000
Let's talk about variable costs.

02:55.000 --> 03:07.000
Variable costs can be divided into proportional, progressive, and degressive, depending on how they change with the increase in the volume of production.

03:07.000 --> 03:14.000
If the variable costs increase directly proportional to the increase in the volume of production,

03:14.000 --> 03:20.000
for example, if the volume of production increases by two times and the variable costs increase by two times,

03:20.000 --> 03:25.000
then we talk about proportional variable costs.

03:25.000 --> 03:29.000
But this is not always the case.

03:29.000 --> 03:39.000
The fact is that proportional variable costs only exist when there are no changes in the production process at the enterprise.

03:39.000 --> 03:46.000
The technology is not improving, there is no increase in labor productivity.

03:47.000 --> 03:55.000
If these processes are implemented at the enterprise, then we have a different form of variable costs.

03:55.000 --> 04:02.000
Variable costs can increase either faster or slower than the volume of production increases.

04:02.000 --> 04:14.000
If labor productivity increases, if production efficiency increases, then variable costs increase slower than the volume of production increases.

04:14.000 --> 04:19.000
Then we talk about degressive variable costs.

04:19.000 --> 04:26.000
For example, the volume of production increased by two times, that is, by 100%, and the variable costs increased by 70%.

04:26.000 --> 04:27.000
Why?

04:27.000 --> 04:35.000
Because the new technology has been implemented, which has allowed to save materials, resources, energy, and fuel.

04:35.000 --> 04:42.000
As a result, the variable costs have increased to a lesser extent than the volume of production.

04:42.000 --> 04:51.000
But unfortunately, there are also progressive costs, when the costs increase faster than the volume of production.

04:51.000 --> 04:58.000
This happens less often, but nevertheless, when the rhythm of production is disrupted,

04:58.000 --> 05:03.000
when labor productivity decreases, when there are failures at the enterprise,

05:04.000 --> 05:12.000
when progressive technology cannot be used, then progressive variable costs take place.

05:12.000 --> 05:16.000
The costs increase faster than the labor productivity increases.

05:16.000 --> 05:23.000
This is the worst possible variant of variable costs.

05:24.000 --> 05:35.000
Depending on the variant chosen, the variables can be distinguished.

05:35.000 --> 05:37.000
The cost-reaction coefficient.

05:39.000 --> 05:43.000
You can see how it is defined on the slide.

05:43.000 --> 05:49.000
The cost-reaction coefficient is defined as the change in costs to the change in the volume of production.

05:50.000 --> 06:01.000
If the cost-reaction coefficient is 1, then the changes in the volume of production and the change in variable costs increase proportionally.

06:01.000 --> 06:10.000
If the coefficient is greater than 1, then the costs increase faster than the volume of production.

06:10.000 --> 06:17.000
And vice versa, if the coefficient is less than 1, then the costs increase slower than the volume of production.

06:18.000 --> 06:28.000
The graph on the slide shows how the costs change with the corresponding increase in the volume of production.

06:28.000 --> 06:32.000
You can see different variants here.

06:32.000 --> 06:41.000
The coefficient is less than 1, and the coefficient is equal to 1 with proportional costs, or K is greater with progressive costs.

06:42.000 --> 06:48.000
This is how the costs increase with the increase in the volume of production.

06:48.000 --> 06:58.000
The theoretical question allows us to approach the consideration of the operation of the enterprise.

06:58.000 --> 07:03.000
We have already discussed three possible variants.

07:03.000 --> 07:05.000
Which one is better?

07:05.000 --> 07:09.000
The most ideal is the degressive variant.

07:09.000 --> 07:15.000
This is when the costs increase slower than the volume of production.

07:15.000 --> 07:17.000
This is the ideal variant.

07:17.000 --> 07:21.000
And the less the coefficient is, the better.

07:23.000 --> 07:28.000
The normal variant, the average variant, is the proportional variant,

07:28.000 --> 07:35.000
when the variable costs and the volume of production increase to the same degree.

